   brand-centered management of a product category when the interbrand
   competition is high but interstore competition is low. Applying the
   intervention analysis methodology, the authors empirically test several
   of these analytical findings, employing a unique data set that contains
   information about a supermarket chain's weekly average unit prices and
   sales of the laundry detergent category before and after this product
   category was moved to CM by the retailer. The propositions that adoption
   of CM will lead to higher retail prices and lower sales are upheld in
   this empirical study. The authors discuss the implications of these
   findings for practitioners and researchers, the limitations of the
   study, and directions for further research.
