AB The authors build on conceptual and analytic evidence to argue that
   firms can increase performance by shifting emphasis away from customer
   retention strategies toward customer acquisition strategies as
   competitive density (i.e., the number of competitors) increases and the
   marketplace becomes more dynamic. Empirical research using four data
   sources for a single artistic industry produces strong support for the
   moderation hypotheses. When competitive density is low, a customer
   retention strategy emphasizing close relationships with customers and
   adaptive learning enhances performance. When competitive density is
   high, a customer acquisition strategy emphasizing innovation and
   competitor learning enhances performance. Four key takeaways emerge. As
   competitive density increases, (1) the financial impact of choosing the
   right mix of resources and capabilities increases; (2) close customer
   relationships become liabilities, providing no revenue benefits and
   exerting a negative effect on net income; (3) close relationships with
   suppliers increase revenues but also expenses, so that net income
   decreases; and (4) adaptive learning lowers revenue and, even more so,
   expenses, so that net income increases. The authors discuss the
   implications of these findings and identify combinations of resources
   and capabilities that achieve different performance objectives.
