   participation and membership duration on the adoption of new products
   from opposing brands as well as from the preferred brand. Longitudinal
   data were collected on the participation behavior, membership duration,
   and adoption behavior of 7506 members spanning four brand communities
   and two product categories. Using a hazard modeling approach, the
   authors find that higher levels of participation and longer-term
   membership in a brand community not only increase the likelihood of
   adopting a new product from the preferred brand but also decrease the
   likelihood of adopting new products from opposing brands. However, such
   oppositional loyalty is contingent on whether a competitor's new product
   is the first to market. Furthermore, in the case of overlapping
   memberships, higher levels of participation in a brand community may
   actually increase the likelihood of adopting products from rival brands.
